    public class PyCommunicator
extends com.anylogic.engine.Agent

    Python Communicator


    Dragging this agent into a model allows you to run Python code as part of your model.


    Available functions, with name and description:

    (See code completion for more info)


















    isConnected Pings the server to check if it's still alive
    run Execute a statement (return void)
    runResults Evaluation an expression (return some results)
    runFile Runs a file and returns the output. Can be used as part of an active object or staticly.

    Note 1: all calls return an Attempt object.

    You can query the success and feedback using the isSuccessful and getFeedback functions.



    In addition to single-line Python code, you can also pass multiline Python code in the form of multiple arguments

    Note 2: For multiline code, make sure all the number of spaces you use for each indentation are consistent.



    Node 3: A history of recently ran commands can be accessed through the variable history located within this object.
    See Also:

      java.util.LinkedList<com.anylogic.engine.Pair<java.lang.String,​Attempt>> history
      Holds the last 500 commands ran by the user, in chronological order (i.e., the first item is the most recently run command).

      Implemented as a list of Pair objects with the command as the first value and the Attempt as the second value.

      For example, to get the code used in the most recent command: history.get(0).getFirst()

      And to get the Attempt used in the most recent command: history.get(0).getSecond()



      Provided as reference for the end-user; for example, if they execute multiple commands sequentially and want the outputs without having to create an object for each call.

      java.lang.String pythonCommand
      The full path to the desired python executable.

      The input of this parameter is used when pythonCommandType is set to "(other)" / PythonCommandType.PYTHON_OTHER.

      For other settings, this parameter's value will be updated to reflect the executable path of the active Python being used.
      PythonCommandType pythonCommandType
      The preferred command to call Python.

      If (other) is selected, you can specify the alias to Python.

      If (path) is selected, you can specify the full path to the desired python executable.
      java.lang.String pythonExecPath
      The absolute path to the Python executable that is desired to be connected to.

      The input of this parameter is used when pythonCommandType is set to "(path)" / PythonCommandType.PYTHON_PATH.

      For other settings, this parameter's value will be updated to reflect the executable path of the active Python being used.
      boolean redirectPyOutput
      Whether to redirect output coming from Python to the AnyLogic console.

      If true, any print statements or warnings from Python will be printed to the AnyLogic console.

      When viewed from the developer panel, standard output will be printed in green and standard error will be printed in red.

      You may change this parameter during run-time to override the initial value.
      static com.anylogic.engine.Scale scale  
      protected com.anylogic.engine.presentation.ShapeText text  
      boolean throwErrorOnFailedAttempt
      Decides whether to throw an AnyLogic model error if any command does not execute successfully.

      In other words: if set to true, errors from Python will cause model-halting errors in AnyLogic.

        public PythonCommandType pythonCommandType
        The preferred command to call Python.

        If (other) is selected, you can specify the alias to Python.

        If (path) is selected, you can specify the full path to the desired python executable.

      • pythonCommand

        public java.lang.String pythonCommand
        The full path to the desired python executable.

        The input of this parameter is used when pythonCommandType is set to "(other)" / PythonCommandType.PYTHON_OTHER.

        For other settings, this parameter's value will be updated to reflect the executable path of the active Python being used.

      • pythonExecPath

        public java.lang.String pythonExecPath
        The absolute path to the Python executable that is desired to be connected to.

        The input of this parameter is used when pythonCommandType is set to "(path)" / PythonCommandType.PYTHON_PATH.

        For other settings, this parameter's value will be updated to reflect the executable path of the active Python being used.

      • throwErrorOnFailedAttempt

        public boolean throwErrorOnFailedAttempt
        Decides whether to throw an AnyLogic model error if any command does not execute successfully.

        In other words: if set to true, errors from Python will cause model-halting errors in AnyLogic.

      • redirectPyOutput

        public boolean redirectPyOutput
        Whether to redirect output coming from Python to the AnyLogic console.

        If true, any print statements or warnings from Python will be printed to the AnyLogic console.

        When viewed from the developer panel, standard output will be printed in green and standard error will be printed in red.

        You may change this parameter during run-time to override the initial value.

      • history

        public java.util.LinkedList<com.anylogic.engine.Pair<java.lang.String,​Attempt>> history
        Holds the last 500 commands ran by the user, in chronological order (i.e., the first item is the most recently run command).

        Implemented as a list of Pair objects with the command as the first value and the Attempt as the second value.

        For example, to get the code used in the most recent command: history.get(0).getFirst()

        And to get the Attempt used in the most recent command: history.get(0).getSecond()



        Provided as reference for the end-user; for example, if they execute multiple commands sequentially and want the outputs without having to create an object for each call.

      • connect

        public void connect()
        Connects to the local Python installation based on the currently set parameters.

      • disconnect

        public void disconnect()
        Disconnects from the local Python installation.

        Executing this function sever the connection to Python. To reconnect, the connect function will need to be called.

      • reset

        public void reset()
        First disconnects from the active Python installation, then reconnects to it.

        Executing this function sever the connection to Python and then reestablish it. This will create a fresh/clean Python environment using the same Python installation previously used.

        If it's desired to change the Python environment that's connected to, first call disconnect, then
